Figure 1. We use a Captioner (Cap) to generate synthetic captions for web images, and a Filter (Filt) to remove noisy captions.

collected from the web. Despite the performance gain obtained by scaling up the dataset, our paper shows that the noisy web text is suboptimal for vision-language learning.
To this end, we propose BLIP: Bootstrapping LanguageImage Pre-training for uniÔ¨Åed vision-language understanding and generation. BLIP is a new VLP framework which enables a wider range of downstream tasks than existing methods. It introduces two contributions from the model and data perspective, respectively:
(a) Multimodal mixture of Encoder-Decoder (MED): a new model architecture for effective multi-task pre-training and Ô¨Çexible transfer learning. An MED can operate either as a unimodal encoder, or an image-grounded text encoder, or an image-grounded text decoder. The model is jointly pre-trained with three vision-language objectives: imagetext contrastive learning, image-text matching, and imageconditioned language modeling.
(b) Captioning and Filtering (CapFilt): a new dataset boostrapping method for learning from noisy image-text pairs. We Ô¨Ånetune a pre-trained MED into two modules: a captioner to produce synthetic captions given web images, and a Ô¨Ålter to remove noisy captions from both the original web texts and the synthetic texts.
We perform extensive experiments and analysis, and make the following key observations.
‚Ä¢ We show that the captioner and the Ô¨Ålter work together to achieve substantial performance improvement on various downstream tasks by bootstrapping the captions. We also Ô¨Ånd that more diverse captions yield larger gains.
‚Ä¢ BLIP achieves state-of-the-art performance on a wide range of vision-language tasks, including image-text re-

