Figure 3. Learning framework of BLIP. We introduce a captioner to produce synthetic captions for web images, and a Ô¨Ålter to remove noisy image-text pairs. The captioner and Ô¨Ålter are initialized from the same pre-trained model and Ô¨Ånetuned individually on a small-scale human-annotated dataset. The bootstrapped dataset is used to pre-train a new model.

We propose Captioning and Filtering (CapFilt), a new method to improve the quality of the text corpus. Figure 3 gives an illustration of CapFilt. It introduces two modules: a captioner to generate captions given web images, and a Ô¨Ålter to remove noisy image-text pairs. Both the captioner and the Ô¨Ålter are initialized from the same pre-trained MED model, and Ô¨Ånetuned individually on the COCO dataset. The Ô¨Ånetuning is a lightweight procedure.
SpeciÔ¨Åcally, the captioner is an image-grounded text decoder. It is Ô¨Ånetuned with the LM objective to decode texts given images. Given the web images Iw, the captioner generates synthetic captions Ts with one caption per image. The Ô¨Ålter is an image-grounded text encoder. It is Ô¨Ånetuned with the ITC and ITM objectives to learn whether a text matches an image. The Ô¨Ålter removes noisy texts in both the original web texts Tw and the synthetic texts Ts, where a text is considered to be noisy if the ITM head predicts it as unmatched to the image. Finally, we combine the Ô¨Åltered image-text pairs with the human-annotated pairs to form a new dataset, which we use to pre-train a new model.
4. Experiments and Discussions
In this section, we Ô¨Årst introduce pre-training details. Then we provide a detailed experimental analysis on our method.
4.1. Pre-training Details
Our models are implemented in PyTorch (Paszke et al., 2019) and pre-trained on two 16-GPU nodes. The image transformer is initialized from ViT pre-trained on ImageNet (Touvron et al., 2020; Dosovitskiy et al., 2021), and the text transformer is initialized from BERTbase (Devlin et al., 2019). We explore two variants of ViTs: ViT-B/16 and ViT-L/16. Unless otherwise speciÔ¨Åed, all results reported in this paper as ‚ÄúBLIP‚Äù uses ViT-B. We pre-train the model for 20 epochs using a batch size of 2880 (ViT-B) /

2400 (ViT-L). We use AdamW (Loshchilov & Hutter, 2017) optimizer with a weight decay of 0.05. The learning rate is warmed-up to 3e-4 (ViT-B) / 2e-4 (ViT-L) and decayed linearly with a rate of 0.85. We take random image crops of resolution 224 √ó 224 during pre-training, and increase the image resolution to 384 √ó 384 during Ô¨Ånetuning. We use the same pre-training dataset as Li et al. (2021a) with 14M images in total, including two human-annotated datasets (COCO and Visual Genome (Krishna et al., 2017)), and three web datasets (Conceptual Captions (Changpinyo et al., 2021), Conceptual 12M (Changpinyo et al., 2021), SBU captions (Ordonez et al., 2011)). We also experimented with an additional web dataset, LAION (Schuhmann et al., 2021), which contains 115M images with more noisy texts1. More details about the datasets can be found in the appendix.
4.2. Effect of CapFilt
In Table 1, we compare models pre-trained on different datasets to demonstrate the efÔ¨Åcacy of CapFilt on downstream tasks, including image-text retrieval and image captioning with Ô¨Ånetuned and zero-shot settings.
When only the captioner or the Ô¨Ålter is applied to the dataset with 14M images, performance improvement can be observed. When applied together, their effects compliment each other, leading to substantial improvements compared to using the original noisy web texts.
CapFilt can further boost performance with a larger dataset and a larger vision backbone, which veriÔ¨Åes its scalability in both the data size and the model size. Furthermore, by using a large captioner and Ô¨Ålter with ViT-L, performance of the base model can also be improved.
1We only download images whose shorter edge is larger than 256 pixels from the original LAION400M. Due to the large size of LAION, we only use 1/5 of it each epoch during pre-training.

